**Long-Acting Reversible Contraception (LARC)**

**IUD (Intrauterine Device):**
- Small T-shaped device placed in uterus
- Hormonal IUD (Mirena, Kyleena, Skyla, Liletta)
- Copper IUD (Paragard)
- Lasts 3-10 years
- Over 99% effective

**Implant (Nexplanon):**
- Small rod inserted under arm skin
- Releases progestin hormone
- Lasts up to 5 years
- Over 99% effective

**Hormonal Methods**

**Birth Control Pills:**
- Take daily at same time
- Prevents ovulation
- 91-99% effective
- Many types available

**Patch (Xulane):**
- Worn on skin (butt, arm, back)
- Changed weekly
- 91-99% effective

**Vaginal Ring (NuvaRing, Annovera):**
- Inserted in vagina
- Left in for 3 weeks
- 91-99% effective

**Shot (Depo-Provera):**
- Injection every 3 months
- 94% effective
- May cause bone density loss with long-term use

**Barrier Methods**

**Condoms:**
- Worn on penis (male) or in vagina (female)
- Protect against STIs
- 82-98% effective
- Used every time

**Diaphragm/Cervical Cap:**
- Dome with rim, covers cervix
- Used with spermicide
- 88-94% effective
- Must be fitted by doctor

**Sponge:**
- Contains spermicide
- Covers cervix
- 76-88% effective
- Available over-the-counter

**Sterilization**

**Tubal Ligation (women):**
- Permanent surgery
- Cuts or blocks fallopian tubes
- Over 99% effective

**Vasectomy (men):**
- Minor surgery
- Cuts vas deferens
- Over 99% effective

**Fertility Awareness:**
- Track cycle, avoid sex during fertile days
- Requires consistent tracking
- 76-88% effective

**Withdrawal:**
- Pulling out before ejaculation
- Not very reliable
- 78% effective

**Emergency Contraception:**
- Morning-after pill
- Can prevent pregnancy after unprotected sex
- Use as soon as possible (within 5 days)
- Copper IUD most effective

**Choosing a Method:**
- How important is effectiveness?
- Do you want children in future?
- Do you need STI protection?
- Are you breastfeeding?
- Do you have any health conditions?

